### Encapsulation in Java

Encapsulation is the mechanism of wrapping data (fields) and code (methods) together as a single unit, and restricting direct access to internal data.

---

### Achieving Encapsulation

1. Declare fields as `private`
2. Provide `public` getter and setter methods
3. Validate data in setter methods

---

### Example

```java
public class Person {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public int getAge() {
        return age;
    }

    public void setAge(int age) {
        if (age > 0 && age < 150) {
            this.age = age;
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Benefits of Encapsulation

| Benefit | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Data Hiding | Internal state is protected |
| Validation | Control what values are assigned |
| Flexibility | Change internal implementation without affecting callers |
| Maintainability | Easier to modify and test |

---

### Read-Only / Write-Only Classes

- Read-only: Provide only getters
- Write-only: Provide only setters

> **Key Point:** Encapsulation is the foundation of Java's security model. Always use private fields with public getters/setters. Never expose internal data structures directly.

codeExample:
class BankAccount {
    private String accountNumber;
    private double balance;

    public BankAccount(String accountNumber) {
        this.accountNumber = accountNumber;
        this.balance = 0.0;
    }

    public String getAccountNumber() {
        return accountNumber;
    }

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }

    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) {
            balance += amount;
        }
    }

    public boolean withdraw(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0 && amount <= balance) {
            balance -= amount;
            return true;
        }
        return false;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount acc = new BankAccount("ACC123");
        acc.deposit(1000);
        acc.withdraw(200);
        System.out.println("Balance: " + acc.getBalance());
    }
}
